KW  - Large language model
AB  - The new energy-oriented transition under the carbon neutrality agenda offers unprecedented opportunities for firms' innovation. This paper quantifies the development signals of the new energy industry (NEDS) in China from the dual perspectives of policy and market through comprehensive textual analysis, using the large language model (LLM) of Qwen 2.5-Max and the improved XLNet model. We demonstrate that NEDS stimulates firms' innovative investment, as reflected in their cross-industry investment in new energy (NECI). Mechanism analysis focusing on the signals' attention, differentiation, and interaction reveals that: First, both policy and market-oriented NEDS effectively enhance firms' attention to new energy and drive their NECI. Second, stronger policy signals focused on optimizing the investment environment, as well as market signals disseminated through more authoritative official media, are both associated with a larger scale of firms' NECI. Third, the interactive effect of different signals diminishes the marginal contribution of the individual signal. Economic consequences analysis further shows that NECI driven by NEDS increases firms' operating incomes in the short term, but reduces their capital returns in the long run. This paper not only reveals the positive role of industrial development signals in firms' innovative investment, but also offers practical support for promoting the efficient development of the new energy industry.
